    "title": {
        "rendered": "Inline Documentation Standards"
    },
    "content": {
        "rendered": "<p>Inline documentation provides a good resource for core developers in future development, and other developers when learning about WordPress. It also provides the information necessary to populate the <a href=\"https://developer.wordpress.org/reference/\">WordPress developer code reference</a>.</p>\n<blockquote><p>\n<strong>I don&#8217;t need to document my code. I wrote all of it &#8211; know it like the back of my hand.</strong></p>\n<p>&#8220;I would argue that, separately, documentation <em>is also</em> for you, the developer. I&#8217;ve found quite often that my inline documentation can be a very effective breadcrumb trail when establishing one&#8217;s own intent, particularly with regard to complex function arguments and usage. And it&#8217;s also helpful to return to a function two years later and find a paragraph in the inline documentation that describes, in meticulous fashion, something that I otherwise would have had to rediscover all over again.&#8221; <em>&#8211; Nacin</em>\n</p></blockquote>\n<h2>Language-specific Standards</h2>\n<ul class=\"sub-menu\">\n<li><a title=\"PHP Documentation Standards\" href=\"https://developer.wordpress.org/coding-standards/inline-documentation-standards/php/\">PHP Documentation Standards</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://developer.wordpress.org/coding-standards/inline-documentation-standards/javascript/\">JavaScript Documentation Standards</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Resources</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://jjj.blog/2012/06/inline-documentation/\">Inline documentation</a> &#8211; why you should</li>\n</ul>\n",
        "protected": false
    },
